Getting bad news across in a way which considers the other person’s emotions.

Do you find it difficult to give someone bad news? Do you try to think of ways to soften the bad news blow? Do you wonder what the best time would be to give someone the bad news? Do you go around the houses or do you get straight to the point? If you’re someone who struggles with these issues, then read through this tool in order to find the best way of getting bad news across to someone. There is never a good time to give bad news and it will often result in emotional reactions. No one likes being the bearer of bad news. You know it’s the right thing to do (I need to dismiss him), but you don’t want to (he has a wife and 2 young children).

The method
It would appear that recipients of bad news often react in a comparable way, namely:

Denial (not possible, that can’t be true);
Anger (you are abusing me);
Bargaining (can I stay if I work some more hours);
Depression (I really don’t know what to do anymore, I’ll have to sell my house);
Acceptance (oh well, if that’s the way it has to be, how many days do I need to work before I leave?).

The bad news conversation steps are based on these reactions. Conversations are structured in accordance with the head-body-tail method. This looks as follows for the bad news conversation:

Head, dealing a blow;
Body, absorbing the blow;
Tail, what now?

Required time
It will take approximately 10 minutes to read through this tool.

